{
  "doc_id": "13991",
  "text": "For a navigation algorithm to be successfully applied in unknown environments, it is essential to have guarantees on both obstacle avoidance and progression towards the goal location. These guarantees need to take the dynamic constraints of the vehicle into account, especially as the speed of the vehicle increases, e.g. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Moreover, the navigation scheme cannot consume too much computational power as the robot must perform other tasks, such as process sensor information and map the environment. To incorporate all of these demands, we build upon the DWA algorithm presented in [CITATION_3] , which possesses all of the mentioned qualities, albeit without a guarantee of progression towards the goal, as noted, for example, in [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] .",
